* A sudden outbreak of the disease has brought the Chinese people their longest Spring Festival holiday in nearly a decade. With the resumption of work on February 10, the city is gradually returning to its former appearance.

A sudden outbreak of the disease has brought the Chinese people their longest Spring Festival holiday in nearly a decade. With the resumption of work on February 10, the city is gradually returning to its former appearance.

This article first appeared at southern weekend and is not to be reprinted without permission

By Liu Shiyang, southern weekly reporter

Responsible Editor | Gu CE

On February 10,2020, the long holiday that had enveloped the city finally came to an end, but the city's recovery still seemed to have to wait.

As early as January 27,2020, the State Council announced the extension of the Spring Festival holiday, and local governments have since followed suit, with most provinces and cities setting the resumption date for February 10.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In Sanlitun, Beijing's busiest city, most shops are closed. (Lau sze-yeung / Photo)

At 8 a.m. , during the morning rush hour, traffic broadcasts in the capital, Beijing, rarely reported that the city was open.

At the East Third Ring Bridge in Guomao, the drivers'right foot is a bit uncomfortable -- in Florida, a junction with a speed limit of 80 km, half the speed is usually not reached, and now it can be exceeded if they are not careful.

Beijing International Trade CBD Under the East Third Ring Bridge is still sleeping in the epidemic. Because there was no traffic, the stoplight at the intersection was too long. The densest public transport station in Dabeiyao and Guomao subway are sparsely populated. Office a change in the past lively, only a few white-collar in the front office after measuring temperature, do not want to stay a minute.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At 9 am, the Empty Beijing International Trade CBD Guanghua Road. (Lau sze-yeung / Photo)

In the epidemic has not yet faded, many people still have some concerns about returning to work.

At 10 a.m. , Li Ran, an accountant in a Shanghai company, put on two layers of face masks and left for work, carrying two spare ones in her bag. Her biggest worry was having lunch. She was afraid to eat takeout and didn't want to take off her mask for so long in public. Her mother told her that she would take the afternoon off if there were more people coming to work.

According to their sample survey, 80 percent of manufacturing enterprises want to return to work, and this proportion has reached 70 percent, Zhang Ying, vice director of the Shanghai Economic and Trade Commission, said at a news conference on Feb. 10. In addition, the software and Information Services Industry, is still home office-based, but also more than 80% began to resume work.

Some star enterprises back to work the influence even spread overseas. Tesla's shares were up 5.47 per cent in pre-market trading on the first day of work at its Shanghai plant. The high-profile new-energy car maker, which had been in the spotlight among Chinese consumers with its low-cost home-made model 3, said deliveries scheduled for early February would be delayed because of the outbreak.

In the GASTRONOMIC, temperate city of Guangzhou, the most striking is the resurgence of the consumer and service industries -- the industries most affected by the outbreak. In a Feb. 10 report, a reporter for the Southern Metropolis Daily said that the opening rate of some stores in Guangzhou has reached 80 percent to 90 percent.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Some barbershops have opened in Guangzhou. (CHEERIOS / Photo)

One owner of a bed-and-breakfast hotel told southern weekend that many restaurant owners he knew were planning to start work, even though some places weren't allowed to. Although the outbreak required minimal contact, he followed tradition and handed out red packets to employees that morning.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
People wear thick protective clothing on the Guangzhou subway. (CHEERIOS / Photo)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In contrast to busy first-tier cities, the resumption of work in other parts of the country will still have to give way to disease control.

In Wenzhou, Zhejiang Province, all enterprises are not allowed to resume work before 2400 hours on February 17, while the resumption date announced by Jingdezhen in Jiangxi Province has been postponed to the 24th. In Zhengzhou, the government requires companies to return to work according to the structure of their employees: local workers, not earlier than February 10, and those with fewer employees in the affected areas can return to work on the 17th. All other companies are expected to resume work on February 24th.

In addition, some cities have adopted the approval system. Hangzhou received applications from nearly 30,000 enterprises before February 10, but only 162 were approved.

Also in need of approval is Shenzhen, where the owner of a Shenzhen company that makes mobile phone accessories told southern weekend that he had submitted his reinstatement documents last week but had not yet received permission. Large and medium sized enterprises are the main ones allowed to resume work in Shenzhen, with Vanke choosing to resume work on February 10, while Huawei has already partially resumed work as early as February 3.

Perhaps it was the panic of the SARS era. Those who work in Beijing seem more conservative about returning to work, and the normally sprawling Zhongguancun software park is still sleeping, 30 km northwest of Beijing's still sleepy Guomao. At 12 noon on February 10, only a few security guards were stationed in front of tencent's headquarters, which used to be heavily trafficked. Netease, Sina and Lenovo were also deserted.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At 11 a.m. , there was no one in front of Netease or Baidu buildings. (Lau sze-yeung / Photo)

The Zhongguancun Software Park used to be the busiest coffee shop and smoking place, only a few people. After working in the area for three years, a programmer from four different companies told southern weekend that he could do his job at home and would not go to work until the epidemic was completely over.

In fact, compared with small and medium-sized enterprises, the Internet giants have been quite humanized plans to resume work. Employees of Baidu, Sohu, Meituan and other large Internet companies told southern weekend that they are still working mainly online this week, and their return dates have all been delayed until after the 17th, while tencent and Toutiao, extended the holiday directly to February 24th.

Guangzhou Street, epidemic prevention personnel stopped vehicles to measure body temperature. (CHEERIOS / Photo)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
According to a recent survey on the impact of the 2020 epidemic on the resumption of work and recruitment, 47 percent of enterprises will resume work on February 10. About 15 percent of the companies returned to work after Feb. 10, and 27 percent, as of Feb. 5, had not yet set a time frame for returning to work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the streets of Guangzhou, there are workstations to check body temperature. (CHEERIOS / Photo)

Among the enterprises that adopted delayed return to work, 55% of enterprises adopted working from home, 32% took leave and had work response, and 13% took normal leave. This shows that the vast majority of companies have adopted online flexible working methods, while 51 per cent of those working from home are in the IT, communications, electronics and Internet industries, according to 58 cities for hire survey data.

A sudden outbreak of the disease has brought the Chinese people their longest Spring Festival holiday in nearly a decade. With the resumption of work on February 10, the city is gradually returning to its former appearance. At nine o'clock in the evening, CCTV reporters, in a live broadcast, took a bus around Beijing. The Lens once again passed over the International Trade CBD, which, under the lighting decoration, seemed to recover a little bit of its former prosperity.

In the absence of an outbreak, the Beijing CBD, a region of less than 10 square kilometers, generated a GDP of 316.3 billion yuan in 2018. Because tens of thousands of enterprises, headquarters and institutions in the region is the most densely populated in Beijing. Jones Lang Lasalle, which also operates here, once counted an average of more than 400,000 people a day.

But, as in many parts of the country, the way it works is changing dramatically.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
People go to work for a temperature check on the Guangzhou subway. (CHEERIOS / Photo)
